<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="116" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="58.[171,1385,287,2652]" pageId="58" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[173,280,1195,1228]" pageId="58" pageNumber="116">Habitat</emphasis>
. Humid, dry deciduous and spiny forests at 
<quantity box="[954,1113,1195,1228]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.05" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="0.1" pageId="58" pageNumber="116" unit="m" value="605.0" valueMax="1200.0" valueMin="10.0">10-1200 m</quantity>
. The Madagascan Straw-colored Fruit Bat is rare or absent from forests without rocky outcrops used for roosting and survives in highly modified landscapes with minimal native vegetation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="116" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="58.[171,1385,287,2652]" pageId="58" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[174,440,1313,1346]" pageId="58" pageNumber="116">Food and Feeding</emphasis>
. Fruits of native and introduced plants are main dietary components of Madagascan Straw-colored Fruit Bats, but they also eat leaves and other plant parts. They appear to prefer native vegetation to introduced plants. It is known to eat 13 different types of fruits from 13 plant species in ten families, including 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Araliaceae" genus="Polyscias" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" pageId="58" pageNumber="116" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Polyscias</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[258,412,1475,1504]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Araliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" pageId="58" pageNumber="116" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Araliaceae</taxonomicName>
), llex (
